[[tab Authorities]]
++ LAS VEGAS
++++ The Foundation
The biggest, baddest authority in town is the Foundation -- technically, Foundation Southwest United States Regional Command. From Site-666 on the Strip, hidden in plain sight as the Luxor Las Vegas, the Foundation keeps a relatively tight rein on demonic activity throughout the city. But even from a veritable fortress, the Foundation is surrounded. It's just not practical to go in throwing around SRAs and slamming demons into containment cells, because there will always be more and really people would just notice even more if Vegas stopped being sinful one day. So instead, the Foundation practices 'creative containment' -- use your noggin. Cut deals with demons to keep them in line. Think about what they want, and use it to your advantage. Hell, hire some of the dumb bastards.

[[div class="blockquote"]]
**R. HOUSE:** Not you, Calendar. You're special.
[[/div]]

Sometimes, you catch more flies with honey.

++++ FBI Unusual Investigations Unit
//Technically//, the establishment clause of the Constitution prevents the federal government from even recognizing Undervegas, let alone operating within it. However, this is the federal government we're talking about; they don't let petty things like "laws" get in the way of a good time. The UIU doesn't have the manpower to meaningfully police Undervegas, and so despite a deep-seated rivalry that extends into outright animosity, they have formed a temporary truce with the Foundation for mutual benefit. Demon organized crime runs straight through the Nexuses, shipping contraband right into Three Portlands; the UIU often send detachments into the city and work with the Foundation to nab the bad guys.

++++ The Nevada Gaming Commission
The NGC is nothing more than a cover for the owners of the biggest casinos -- demons, wouldn't you know it -- to 'regulate' themselves. They oppose the Foundation's efforts at every possible turn, trying to maximize profits for themselves. However, they are Greed demons, and would sell each other up the river for half a poker chip at the drop of a hat. If they ever worked together, the Foundation might be in trouble. Thankfully, that doesn't seem likely.

++ UNDERVEGAS
++++ Pit Bosses
As mentioned, Undervegas is broken up into seven inequally-sized 'Estates' for each of the deadly sins-- Moneypit (Greed) The Feast (Gluttony), Ivory Towers (Pride), Iwannit (Envy), The Beat (Wrath), Acedia (Sloth), and Succubustown (take a guess). Demons come from all over Hell, end up staying and forming their own little place. The Estates are //very// different, but united in that the most powerful demon of each class ends up taking control of that estate as the Pit Boss. Moneypit's Pit Boss is Ba'al, The Feast's is Belial, Ivory Towers' is Asmodeus, and Succubustown is ruled by the ever-graceful Gamory. The remaining Pit Bosses are, as of yet, unidentified.

++++ Satan
Prince of darkness, Lucifer, et cetera. He's an asshole. Current intel suggests he's still frozen in an ice cube at the bottom of Hell, but he can still cast out his spirit to possess others and cause problems on his behalf -- usually for no clear reason except that he thinks it's funny. Asshole.
[[/tab]] 

[[tab CLASSIFIED]]
++ So you wanna write for Undervegas?
Chiefly, Undervegas is a setting rather than a defined series or canon, so really as long as you get the general premise right (Las Vegas Is Demons), you should be good to include in whatever you're doing.

But if you wanna write something more //focused// on Undervegas, there's a few things to keep in mind. Upfront, not the easiest thing to write for, for one simple reason: you gotta be funny. Undervegas articles tend to be comedic, which is a hard thing to master and intensely subjective at the best of times. But here's a few pointer and guidelines.

**Dialogue.** Dialogue, dialogue, dialogue. This is where the funny comes from, this is where the character comes from, this is where the setting comes from! Undervegas is at its best when you're doing funny dialogue comedy, rapid back-and-forths between characters, witticisms and insults and everything else. An Undervegas article without dialogue is like a burger without a patty.

**Don't worry too much about 'canon' or lore or whatever.** Really, the only hard rule I have is that Undervegas stuff tends to be set in the 90s to 00s; beyond that, go wild. Never let lore get in the way of a good joke.

**Everyone sucks.** Don't be afraid to make your characters just absolutely terrible, insufferable people. They're comedy archetypes -- lean into it, make it so that it's funny when bad things happen to them, even if we're rooting for them. 
[[/tab]]
[[/tabview]]
